<emphasis box="[145,296,367,391]" italics="true" pageId="13">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[145,686,408,430]" box="[145,686,408,430]" pageId="13">
<materialsCitation box="[145,680,408,430]" location="East Palaearctic" pageId="13" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Orientale">
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:8E6487BBFFFEFF8AFCEDFBAAFDD60620:03126076FFF8FF8AFF55FE5FFEC203EB" box="[145,331,408,430]" name="East Palaearctic" pageId="13" stateProvince="Orientale">East Palaearctic</location>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[388,484,408,430]" country="Republic of the Congo" name="Orientale" pageId="13">Oriental</collectingRegion>
regions (
<figureCitation box="[589,670,408,430]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="8.[164,242,1254,1276]" captionTargetBox="[165,1445,197,1213]" captionTargetId="figure-288@8.[163,1447,195,1214]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 5. A, the revised distribution of genera and their alpha diversity. B, the putative dispersal routes recovered by the analysis of the pruned dataset. The grey lines designate dispersal barriers that were never crossed by the Lycini." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5299923" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5299923/files/figure.png" pageId="13">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
)
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[145,254,481,505]" box="[145,254,481,505]" pageId="13">
<emphasis box="[145,254,481,505]" italics="true" pageId="13">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[145,762,521,1126]" pageId="13">
The concept of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Motschulsky" authorityYear="1861" box="[348,494,522,543]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Lycostomus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[348,494,522,543]" italics="true" pageId="13">Lycostomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been very wide and merged all Nearctic, Neotropical, Palaearctic and 
<collectingRegion box="[203,310,582,604]" country="Republic of the Congo" name="Orientale" pageId="13">Oriental</collectingRegion>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laporte" authorityYear="1836" box="[322,400,582,604]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lycini">Lycini</taxonomicName>
without pronounced sexual polymorphism in the shape of elytra (
<figureCitation box="[623,753,613,635]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="10.[163,243,1753,1775]" captionTargetBox="[166,1443,198,1706]" captionTargetId="figure-26@10.[163,1449,195,1713]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 6. Lycus pallidus (F.), male unless stated otherwise. A, general appearance, ventral view. B, apical part of the rostrum, ventral view. C, antenna. D, head, dorsal view. E, prothorax and head, ventral view. F, pronotum, dorsal view. G, meso- and metasternum, ventral view; mesosternum. H, ventral view. I, mesothoracic spiracle with attached trachea. J, abdomen. K, abdomen of Neolycus fernandezi (Dugès), male. L, female terminal ventrite. M, female terminal tergite. N, terminal abdominal segments. O, male genitalia. P, ovipositor. Q, female internal genital duct. R, metatarsus. S, N." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5299925" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5299925/files/figure.png" pageId="13">Figs 6U–X</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[145,212,644,665]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="12.[163,242,1805,1827]" captionTargetBox="[227,1379,198,1757]" captionTargetId="figure-25@12.[224,1382,195,1765]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 7. General appearance. A, Lipernes sp. 3, male. B, Lipernes sp. 1, male. C, Lipernes sp. 1, female. D, Lipernes sp. 2, male. E, ditto, female. F, Lipernes sp. 4, male. G, Lipernes sp. 5, male. H, Lipernes sp. 6, male. I, Lipernes sp. 7, male. J, Lipernes sp. 8, male. K, Lipernes sp. 9, male. L, Lipernes sp. 13, male. M, Lipernes sp. 14, male. N, Lipernes sp. 14, male. O," figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5299927" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5299927/files/figure.png" pageId="13">7A–Q</figureCitation>
). The Neotropical and Nearctic species have to be transferred from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Motschulsky" authorityYear="1861" box="[431,570,675,696]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Lycostomus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[431,570,675,696]" italics="true" pageId="13">Lycostomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1881" box="[614,754,674,695]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Rhyncheros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[614,754,674,695]" italics="true" pageId="13">Rhyncheros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Palaearctic and 
<collectingRegion box="[359,466,705,727]" country="Republic of the Congo" name="Orientale" pageId="13">Oriental</collectingRegion>
species represent two independent lineages and must be placed in redefined 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[145,243,767,788]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Lipernes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[145,243,767,788]" italics="true" pageId="13">Lipernes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Motschulsky" authorityYear="1861" box="[299,430,767,788]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Lycostomus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[299,430,767,788]" italics="true" pageId="13">Lycostomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. We found that the species of the deeply rooted Asian clade (
<figureCitation box="[510,576,797,819]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="1.[145,223,1543,1565]" captionTargetBox="[147,1426,1001,1502]" captionTargetId="figure-248@1.[145,1428,999,1503]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figure 2. The distribution and alpha diversity of the Lycini as defined until the present analysis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5299917" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5299917/files/figure.png" pageId="13">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) have genitalia similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Waterhouse, 1879" authorityName="Waterhouse. AK, AL" authorityYear="1879" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Lipernes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perspectus">
<emphasis box="[373,606,828,849]" italics="true" pageId="13">Lipernes perspectus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Waterhouse CO" pageId="13" refId="ref17663" refString="Waterhouse CO. 1879. Illustrations of typical specimens in the collection of the British Museum. Part 1. Lycidae. London: Taylor and Francis." type="book" year="1879">Waterhouse, 1879</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore, we use the name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[567,670,859,880]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Lipernes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[567,670,859,880]" italics="true" pageId="13">Lipernes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for the designation of this clade. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[457,560,890,911]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Lipernes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[457,560,890,911]" italics="true" pageId="13">Lipernes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Motschulsky" authorityYear="1861" box="[624,761,890,911]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Lycostomus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[624,761,890,911]" italics="true" pageId="13">Lycostomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occur sympatrically, and they can be distinguished only using male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[498,570,950,972]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="12.[163,242,1805,1827]" captionTargetBox="[227,1379,198,1757]" captionTargetId="figure-25@12.[224,1382,195,1765]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 7. General appearance. A, Lipernes sp. 3, male. B, Lipernes sp. 1, male. C, Lipernes sp. 1, female. D, Lipernes sp. 2, male. E, ditto, female. F, Lipernes sp. 4, male. G, Lipernes sp. 5, male. H, Lipernes sp. 6, male. I, Lipernes sp. 7, male. J, Lipernes sp. 8, male. K, Lipernes sp. 9, male. L, Lipernes sp. 13, male. M, Lipernes sp. 14, male. N, Lipernes sp. 14, male. O," figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5299927" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5299927/files/figure.png" pageId="13">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
AA–AR). Their general appearance is similar; most species are red or red and black in colour (
<figureCitation box="[422,538,1012,1034]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="12.[163,242,1805,1827]" captionTargetBox="[227,1379,198,1757]" captionTargetId="figure-25@12.[224,1382,195,1765]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 7. General appearance. A, Lipernes sp. 3, male. B, Lipernes sp. 1, male. C, Lipernes sp. 1, female. D, Lipernes sp. 2, male. E, ditto, female. F, Lipernes sp. 4, male. G, Lipernes sp. 5, male. H, Lipernes sp. 6, male. I, Lipernes sp. 7, male. J, Lipernes sp. 8, male. K, Lipernes sp. 9, male. L, Lipernes sp. 13, male. M, Lipernes sp. 14, male. N, Lipernes sp. 14, male. O," figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5299927" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5299927/files/figure.png" pageId="13">Figs 7A–Z</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[552,616,1012,1033]" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="14.[163,241,1788,1810]" captionTargetBox="[166,1444,767,1739]" captionTargetId="figure-183@14.[163,1449,764,1748]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 8. General appearance. A, Lycostomus sp. 3. B, C, Lycostomus sp. 4. D–F, Lycostomus sp. 12. G, H, Lycostomus sp. 16. I, Lycostomus sp. 18. J, Lycostomus sp. 19. K, L, Lycostomus sp. 8. M, Lycostomus modestus (sp. 13). N, Lycostomus sp. 19. O, pronotum and head, Lycostomus sp. 4. P–R, male genitalia. P, Lycostomus sp. 10. Q, Lycostomus sp. 9. R, Lycostomus sp. 8. Scale bars: 3 mm (A–O); 1 mm (P–R)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5299929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5299929/files/figure.png" pageId="13">8A–O</figureCitation>
). The length of the apical palpomere, which was originally used as a diagnostic character, is variable in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[573,672,1074,1095]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Lipernes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[573,672,1074,1095]" italics="true" pageId="13">Lipernes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as has been noted already by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kazantsev SV" box="[402,600,1104,1126]" pageId="13" pagination="49 - 68" refId="ref16136" refString="Kazantsev SV. 1993. Lycides nouveaux ou peu connus de l'Indochine (Coleoptera). Bulletin du Museum National d'Histoire naturelle 15 (A): 49 - 68." type="journal article" year="1993">Kazantsev (1993)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
